	<h3>Pressure-Treated Pine</h3>
	<p>Most common wood fence material in Stockton:</p>

	<p><strong>Expected Lifespan: 12-15 years in Stockton climate</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Optimal conditions (excellent maintenance):</strong> 15-18 years</li>
		<li><strong>Typical conditions (moderate maintenance):</strong> 12-15 years</li>
		<li><strong>Neglected (no maintenance):</strong> 8-10 years</li>
		<li><strong>First signs of failure:</strong> 8-10 years (minor rot, warping)</li>
		<li><strong>Replacement typically needed:</strong> 12-15 years</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Degradation Timeline:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Years 0-3:</strong> Fence looks good, minimal issues if properly installed</li>
		<li><strong>Years 4-7:</strong> Sun-exposed sides show fading, minor warping in some boards</li>
		<li><strong>Years 8-10:</strong> Visible wear, some boards cracking, possible post loosening</li>
		<li><strong>Years 11-13:</strong> Multiple boards deteriorating, posts showing rot below ground</li>
		<li><strong>Years 14+:</strong> Widespread failure, extensive repairs needed or replacement</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Lifespan Factors:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Extends life:</strong> Regular staining/sealing, concrete post setting, good drainage, pressure-treated contact wood rating</li>
		<li><strong>Reduces life:</strong> Clay soil contact, neglected maintenance, south/west exposure, water pooling at posts</li>
		<li><strong>Climate impact:</strong> Central Valley heat/sun reduces typical 15-20 year lifespan to 12-15 years</li>
	</ul>

